  <p>The highlighted cell is our base case. Notice how sensitive the result is to the discount rate — a 1% change swings the value by ~$40-60/share. This is why we disclose our exact assumptions.</p>

  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Debt reduction:</strong> If Verizon aggressively pays down its enormous debt pile, the enterprise value to equity value bridge improves drastically, pushing the share price up.</li>
    <li><strong>Price hikes:</strong> With limited competition (essentially an oligopoly with AT&T and T-Mobile), Verizon has pricing power. If they raise plan prices without losing subscribers, FCF grows faster than 2%.</li>
    <li><strong>5G monetization:</strong> Better-than-expected returns on 5G infrastructure through home internet or enterprise solutions.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Interest rates:</strong> Verizon has ~$181B in debt. If interest rates stay "higher for longer," refinancing debt becomes vastly more expensive, directly destroying equity value.</li>
    <li><strong>Intense competition:</strong> T-Mobile has aggressively taken market share. If Verizon has to cut prices or increase promotions to keep subscribers, cash flow will suffer.</li>
    <li><strong>Capital intensity:</strong> Telecom is an inherently expensive business. There is always a new network to build (6G is next). If capex needs exceed expectations, FCF will fall.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use DCF instead of a dividend discount model (DDM) for a telecom?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">While a Dividend Discount Model is common for telecoms since they pay most of their earnings as dividends, a DCF using Free Cash Flow captures the *total* cash the business generates, regardless of management's payout policy. It's a more comprehensive measure of underlying business value.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why is Verizon's Net Cash negative?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Telecoms are capital-intensive utilities. Verizon has ~$181 billion in total debt against only ~$19 billion in cash, resulting in roughly negative $162 billion in net cash. The DCF subtracts this net debt from Enterprise Value to find the Equity Value.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why 2% FCF growth?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">The wireless market in the US is saturated. Almost everyone has a smartphone. Growth only comes from minor price increases or population growth. 2% is a realistic long-term assumption for a mature telecom.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, time horizon, tax situation, and conviction in the assumptions. We provide the tools and transparency — you make the decision.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

